The Influence Of Signature Lines On Teammates Around The NBA

written and coded by Molly Peot

The importance of fashion on and off the court has been on the rise over the past several years in the NBA. A lot of players strive to be the most stylish person off the court with high-end fashion. On the court, players assert their dominance by having the hottest heat on their feet. Many notable stars around the NBA wear multiple player edition and special edition color way sneakers through out the season to try and win the crown of having the best kicks.

There are many things that influence an NBA player when he decides what shoes to wear including brand names, lucrative endorsement deals, performance and style. One factor fans rarely discuss is if teammates of players with signature lines feel compelled to support their teammate by wearing their sneaker. The map below displays the influence of popular stars with signature lines on their teammates shoe choice. For instance out of the 15 players on the Los Angeles Lakers’ roster, eight of them choose to wear Kobe Bryant’s signature Nike line. Although not all eight of them wear Kobe’s shoe every game, they can be seen wearing his line on a frequent basis. Kobe has a strong influence on his teammate with 50% of them choosing his shoe.

On the other hand, five stars shown on the map have zero influence over their teammates. One of those players is the reigning MVP Stephen Curry. Curry is the only player on the Golden State Warriors who wears the Curry signature line. In fact, he is even the only person wearing Under Armour. If the reigning MVP and arguably most talked about player in the NBA has no teammates wearing his line, then what determines influence?

The sole fact that a teammate has a signature line will not influence teammates to also wear the shoe. There are a couple factors that when in place result in higher acceptance. A player does not need all of these factors, but the more they have the higher the use. The first one is brand name. If the signature line is Nike or adidas, the two most dominant brands in the NBA, teammates are more likely to wear the shoe. A strong brand name is more likely to be accepted because of two important reasons. The first reason is that an older, more respected brand has developed trust through out the years with many generations of athletes. The last reason is because of a “coolness” factor. All people are influenced by other people’s perceptions and want to wear what is “in” right now. Secondly, the longer the signature line has been around, the higher percentage of teammates wear the shoe. Lastly, the performance of the signature athlete helps gain acceptance of the shoe. This is measured by regular season and finals MVPs, and championships.

These three guidelines are supported by all situations displayed on the map. For instance, the players tied with the highest acceptance of eight are Kobe Bryant and LeBron James with their Nike signature lines. Both of these athletes individually have a random combination of eight MVPs and championships. Additionally, LeBron has had 22 different models when you add up his 13 signature line models and nine soldier line models, while Kobe is on his 10th signature model.

Carmelo Anthony of the New York Knicks has had a signature line since 2004, but he fails to meet the other two guidelines and therefore does not have any teammates wearing his shoes. Jordan Brand, a subsidiary of Nike, provides Anthony with his signature line. Although it is an extremely popular brand, it is being worn by almost 250 less players than Nike around the NBA, according to hoopshype.com. Anthony also does not have any MVPs or championships to add performance influence.

The same logic can be used to explain why Chris Paul of the Los Angeles Clippers does not have teammates wearing his Jordan brand shoe. Although he is one of the most popular players in the league, other Clippers are not wearing his shoe, which has been around since 2008.

The data trends examined in this piece prove there are reasons behind why some shoes are accepted more than others. Players are always looking for a way to improve their game and many believe shoes play a factor in performance. A young NBA player’s shoe choice will be influenced by teammates who they look up to and view as successful. Once signature line athlete gains respect through seniority and performance, their shoe will become more influential.

Note: This piece was researched, designed, written and coded for a class project. If you notice any errors in my data collection, please feel free to reach out to me via mollypeot (at) gmail (dot) com.
